I'll add on to what I said in >>46296485 and talk about >>46298635

Your story has a pace, and how you introduce it (and what/how many elements you reveal first) depends on that.
This is quite evident with longer pieces like aleph's, Deco's, TIARA's, Happy's, Salty's, or derr's from the OP.
Some stories (I'm looking at you, Happy) are on the dense side in terms of information. Nothing wrong with that, but the writefag has to make sure there's a hook so the reader remembers the most important bits. And I bring him up specifically because I think he's got layers of misdirection in plain sight because of the type of story he's telling.
The kind of tension between characters is going to be really different between his story and in aleph's stuff. Different setting, different characters.
And that brings to mind what kind of setting you're using. aleph? Kinda /adhg/ish reptile alien invaders. Deco? Airships with a CS influence. TIARA? XCom. Happy? Kinda noir retro. Salty? Sci-fi guy stranded on a lower-tech world. derr? High School.
The characters are molded by the environment and vice versa. And I'll bet all of them have much more info than they put into the story.
You have to pick the ones that the readers need now or really soon. The rest is spice. Don't use too much, but don't make it bland.

Basically, write, read, revise, and repeat until done. It's like making soup.

And to elaborate. What your characters' day to day lives look like can affect what situations they get into. For example: the bank teller probably wouldn't go to a demo derby, or maybe he would and that would be something unexpected/interesting. It all depends on what you're going for.
I'm assuming you have no experience creating a plot to something, so I'll say you should think about how you want your story to start, and how you want it to end. It's as important to think about where you want to stop writing, as where you want to start writing, because you can't finish a race with no finish line, if you catch my drift. That is the bare bones basics: think of a start point and an end point and create what you want to happen in between those two points. You can also think about over arching themes you'd want in your story (or even a moral or two if you're feeling fancy), before establishing the start and the end, to help guide you in what direction you want the story to go in. I could go in more detail about themes and stuff, but I'm not a Language arts teacher. There's probably better resources out there than me.
